10.body:
Some languages have automatic collection of unused memory Java, NodeJS they keep track of references using memory Others require manual memory management like C, C++ allocations and removal must be done manually, fast but error prone, a double deallocate is a bug, a missed deallocate is a memory leak, sometimes this is also misused as a feature Rust uses a slightly different concept of ownership. Where variables are kept track by an owner and the value dropped once this single owner is out of scope { // s is not valid here, it’s not yet declared let s = "hello"; // s is valid from this point forward // do stuff with s
} // this scope is now over, and s is no longer valid
10.title: Its all about the memory

18.body:
Rust natively supports parallel programming but we also have some cool things: rayon simplified data parallelism with iterators in Rust. This automatically spins up threads on separate CPUs. use rayon::prelude::*; fn sum_of_squares(input: &[i32]) -> i32 { input.par_iter() // -> Parallel iterator .map(|&i| i * i) .sum()
}

22.body:
cargo is the package manager for Rust that pulls in packages from crates.io and provides many similar functions to npm. A simple registry can be implemented in Git. cargo provides a number of commands for building, cleaning, installing and publishing packages. Some of the commands we will be using are: #Create a new cargo package
cargo init #Run a binary or example of the local package
cargo run #Build this package's and its dependencies' documentation
cargo doc #Run the tests
cargo test
